		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014"></a><br><code>sle2014/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Bounded Seas: Island Parsing Without Shipwrecks</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JanKurš.html">Jan Kurš</a>, <a href="../profile/MirceaLungu.html">Mircea Lungu</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarNierstrasz.html">Oscar Nierstrasz</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_4">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_4</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2014s/paper06.html"><em>Bounded seas</em></a> (SLE 2014 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The core contribution is a parsing technique (island grammars) for robust/partial language processing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL">T2A: Lifecycle</span></a><ul><li> It supports error recovery and robust parsing when dealing with incomplete or noisy source input.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> The technique is motivated by practical manipulation of general-purpose programming language code.
</li></ul></li></ul>
